{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520125"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:20:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:20:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13154"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13154"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.42,0.16,0.2,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5591"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105786"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5591"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13154"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88254"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1747"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9510"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10285"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14854"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38053"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105786"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-month history of increasing fatigue and generalised weakness, associated with a fever over the last week. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 112/74 mmHg, respiratory rate 15/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38\u00b0C. Examination of the oral cavity shows multiple petechiae. Her liver edge is palpable, and her spleen can be felt 3 cm below the costal margin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 90 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 30 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count 39 x 10^9/L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood film shows numerous promyelocytes with heavy granulation and multiple Auer rods. Bone marrow karyotype showed translocation between chromosomes 15 and 17.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following complications is this patient most at risk of developing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tumour lysis syndrome","Disseminated intravascular coagulation","Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura","Leukostasis","Central nervous system infiltration"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation highly suggests acute promyelocytic leukaemia (APML), a subtype of acute myeloid leukaemia characterised by a translocation between chromosomes 15 and 17, carrying the PML and RARA genes, respectively. The blood film findings of promyelocytes with heavy granulation and Auer rods, along with bone marrow karyotype showing translocation between chromosomes 15 and 17, are diagnostic for APML.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC)\u003C/strong\u003E is the most significant and life-threatening complication of APML. The thrombocytopenia and petechiae in this patient may suggest concomitant DIC. This can be confirmed by testing for fibrinogen (reduced) and D-dimer (increased). Blood film may also show schistocytes as a result of microangiopathic haemolysis. APML cells release procoagulant and fibrinolytic substances, leading to a consumptive coagulopathy. This puts patients at high risk of severe bleeding complications, which can be fatal if not promptly recognised and treated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETumour lysis syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in patients with high-burden leukaemias, particularly after initiation of chemotherapy. While possible in APML, it is less common than DIC and typically occurs immediately after starting therapy, particularly in cases with a high white cell count.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura\u003C/strong\u003E (TTP) is a rare disorder characterised by microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, thrombocytopenia, and microvascular thrombosis. It is caused by a deficiency of ADAMTS13, which ultra-large von Willebrand multimers. It is not associated with APML. The abnormal promyelocytes and PML::RARA fusion described in this case are specific for APML and not seen in TTP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeukostasis\u003C/strong\u003E, a medical emergency, describes the end-organ complications associated with hyperleukocytosis (typically defined as a white cell count of \u0026gt;100 x 10^9/L). This is less common in APML. In addition, the white cell count in this case, while elevated, is not in the range typically associated with leukostasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral nervous system (CNS) infiltration\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in acute leukemia, but it is not the most immediate concern in this presentation. CNS infiltration is uncommon in APML.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of APML involves prompt initiation of all-trans retinoic acid (ATRA) and arsenic trioxide, along with aggressive supportive care to manage the coagulopathy. Early recognition and treatment are crucial due to the high risk of early mortality from bleeding complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute promyelocytic leukaemia (APML) is a subtype of acute myeloid leukaemia characterised by a translocation between chromosomes 15 and 17, resulting in PML::RARA fusion.","Disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) is a common and potentially life-threatening complication of APML.","Early recognition and treatment of APML is crucial due to the high risk of severe bleeding complications."],"references":["Yilmaz M, Kantarjian H, Ravandi F. Acute promyelocytic leukemia current treatment algorithms. Blood Cancer J. 2021 Jun 30;11(6):1\u20139. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34193815/","Halfdanarson TR, Hogan WJ, Madsen BE. Emergencies in Hematology and Oncology. Mayo Clinic Proceedings. 2017 Apr 1;92(4):609\u201341. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28385197/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88254"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13154"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88254"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-13T18:06:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-13T18:06:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5591"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105786"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"g